the petition filed by the consumer group claims twa could be put 
on the brink of bankruptcy by the transaction which also has 
been denounced by twas unions 
a suit filed by the air line pilots association in the new york 
supreme court asks that the court prevent icahn from looting 
twa through the stock transaction plan it maintains that icahn 
will strip twa of 665 million and threaten the airlines 
economic future 
the consumer federation told the department that air travelers 
holding nearly 500 million in advance and unused tickets as well 
as credits on twa frequent flyer programs stand to loose 
substantial amounts should twa go bankrupt or be forced to cut 
service or routes 
the federation alleged that icahn who purchased twa in 1985 
when it was near collapse has run up large debts at the company 
while holding on to large amounts of cash cash equivalents and 
marketable securities but the petition alleges most of those cash 
assets will be wiped out in the stock transaction 
the precarious financial structure after this transaction 
raises serious questions about whether the airline will be able to 
meet its financial and quality of service obligations to the 
public said mark cooper director of research for the consumer 
federation 
after running up huge amounts of debt the icahnled group now 
proposes to take all its money and then some out of twa leave the 
company with absolutely no equity and leave the airline on the 
brink of bankruptcy he continued 
furthermore the federation maintained that consumers are 
virtual captives of twa because of its domination in several 
cities such as st louis where more than 80 percent of all 
flights are operated by twa 
the failure of the airline or a significant reduction in 
service would have a devastating impact on these consumers who have 
few alternatives for air travel said cooper 
twa officials in st louis and new york did not immediately 
return calls seeking comment wednesday 
