<TEXT>
investigators of last months delta air lines 
crash in texas are trying to determine whether several click 
sounds on the jets cockpit voice recorder are indications the 
flight crew set the flaps before takeoff 
the boeing 727 crashed seconds after taking off from the 
dallasfort worth airport aug 31 killing 14 of the 108 people 
aboard the investigation has focused on whether a false flap 
setting may have kept the plane from gaining altitude 
at least two clicks can be heard on the recording according to 
sources close to the investigation but additional sounds also are 
being studied to determine the exact number of clicks and whether 
they relate directly to the flaps position 
the flaps which provide an aircraft with lift during takeoff 
were supposed to have been set at 15 degrees for proper takeoff of 
flight 1141 
the dallas morning news on wednesday quoted national 
transportation safety board officials it did not name as saying 
they were studying the possibility that the flaps were extended 
but not far enough 
what you hear on the tape of the cockpit conversation are 
two clicks in quick succession that means that the flaps were at 
least at the 5degree setting the newspaper quoted one source as 
saying 
the boeing 727 has flap settings of 2 5 and 15 degrees the 
flap control mechanism in the cockpit has notches that produce 
clicking sounds as the lever is moved 
meanwhile investigators are expected to conduct tests in flight 
simulators to determine what minimum flap setting would have been 
required for the plane to gain proper lift 
some aviation experts who have followed the accident 
investigation say the boeing 727 which was not fully loaded 
should have been able to take off even with a lower than optimum 
flap setting 
drucella anderson a spokeswoman for the ntsb said wednesday 
the safety board would have no comment on what investigators are 
examining on the cockpit voice recorder tapes 
investigators have uncovered conflicting evidence as to the 
jets flap setting at the time of takeoff 
the voice recorder shows the copilot acknowledged having set 
the flaps to 15 degrees during the routine preflight checklist 
fifteen fifteen green the copilot was heard to say on 
the cockpit recorder tape according to sources involved in the 
investigation 
one source suggested that the copilot if he set the flaps 
probably did so earlier and was reading off the flap setting at the 
time his response was recorded 
the reference to green refers to a light showing the 
position of separate control surfaces on the forward edge of the 
wings called slats a green light shows them to be in the extended 
position 
slats also are supposed to be extended during takeoff but 
investigators have said they found the slats on the wrecked 
aircraft in an unlocked but retracted position 
investigators have said the jack screws on the wings also 
indicated the flaps were in a retracted position and the flapslat 
control lever in the cockpit was found in an up position 
indicating the flaps were retracted the copilot who was 
responsible for setting the flaps has told investigators he cannot 
remember anything after the aircraft was pushed back from the gates 
