<TEXT>
prime minister rajiv gandhi on thursday 
withdrew a defamation bill that journalists and opposition 
politicians charged was an attempt at censorship 
we praise all good deeds by the government said prithvis 
chakravarthy an editor of the calcuttabased bengalilanguage 
newspaper aajkal and member of the editors guild of india this 
withdrawal is one of the few good acts committed by the government 
in a long time and we welcome it 
in a statement gandhi said he was withdrawing the bill because 
it has aroused misapprehensions and misgivigs among the press 
and public 
the law would have expanded the concept of defamation and 
abolished any presumption of innocence by journalists or others 
making disclosures construed as defamatory 
it permitted up to two years imprisonment for first offenders 
and up to five years imprisonment for subsequent convictions 
the government had said the legislation would protect people 
from irresponsible journalism newspapers denounced it as 
fascist and undemocratic and said it was an attempt to 
muzzle the press after a year of reports of alleged kickbacks 
involving defense contracts 
prominent indians including some of gandhis friends have been 
accused of receiving millions of dollars to facilitate contracts 
for swedens bofors artillery guns and west german submarines 
gandhi has denied receiving any money and a government inquiry 
failed to note any wrongdoing 
