<TEXT>
science literacy among americas school 
children is at an alarming and depressing level that may 
prevent many high school graduates from doing well in skilled jobs 
or collegelevel course according to a study released thursday 
the science report card a federally funded project 
conducted by the educational testing service of princeton nj 
found that more than half of the nations 17yearolds are so 
poorly educated in science that they cannot benefit from special 
job training and cannot perform work requiring basic technical 
understanding 
only seven percent of the 17yearolds in the study demonstrated 
sufficient skills to do well in collegelevel science courses 
albert shanker president of the american federation of 
teachers called the findings depressing and alarming and said 
the poor level of science education could be disastrous for the 
country 
the science report card reflects data collected in 1986 it is 
the fifth national study of science skills among 9 13 and 
17yearolds to be conducted by the nea since 1969 
among the findings 
science achievement remains well below the results of the 1969 
study for students at age 17 although there was a slight upturn 
observed in the 1982 and 1986 surveys 
declines in science achievement are less for pupils aged 9 and 
13 but the average achievement at age 13 remains below that 
measured in 1970 and achievement at age 9 has only now returned to 
the level measured in 1970 
science proficiency for black and hispanic students aged 13 and 
17 remains at least four years behind the levels of white students 
of the same ages 
a marked difference in science proficiency is measured between 
girls and boys at the 13 and 17 age levels although the genders 
measure approximately the same at age 9 at age 17 half of the 
males demonstrate an ability to analyze scientific procedures and 
data while only a third of the females have such skills in the 
study of physics the study said the gender gap is extremely 
large by the 11th grade 
mary hatwood futrell president of the national education 
association said the findings paint a stark picture of science 
education in our nations schools 
scientific understanding is more and more a prerequisite for 
informed citizenship said ms futrell if americas citizens 
of tomorrow are not scientifically literate we place our very 
democracy at risk 
she said that the lower level of science achievement by females 
and minority students is the most disturbing of the findings 
by many measures of science proficiency the inequalities for 
both minorities and females actually increase as students move 
through the grades she said 
shanker in a statement released by the american federation of 
teachers said the findings could be troubling for americas future 
when only a small number of our students can understand basic 
scientific concepts the results are disastrous for the entire 
country he said here we are one of the great scientific 
giants of the world and almost 60 percent of our successful 
17yearolds dont have the scientific literacy required of 
informed citizens 
the science report card reinforces results of an international 
study released earlier this year that showed american school 
children at all levels performed far behind children of the same 
age in most of the other 14 nations surveyed 
the science report card study is financed by the department of 
education as part of a program called the national assessment of 
educational progress national report cards also are issued in 
other subjects as part of the program 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

