<TEXT>
the federal election commission took a step 
thursday toward partial closing of a loophole that allows political 
parties to pour millions of soft money dollars indirectly into 
presidential election campaigns 
the independent regulatory agency is under federal court order 
to clarify its vague rules on soft money which is banned in 
federal elections but permitted in state and local contests 
the commission unanimously agreed wednesday to publish a notice 
in the federal register seeking public comment on proposed rule 
changes governing soft money 
the new rules proposals include alternative methods of 
allocating funds that benefit both federal and local election 
activities these include payment of administrative expenses and 
financing of voter registration drives 
the fec changes also could result in substantial bookkeeping 
requirements on state and local political organizations 
soft money includes union and corporate donations as well as 
individual contributions that exceed the federal limit of 1000 
per candidate 
national political parties are limited to spending 8 million 
each toward electing a presidential candidate but they accept 
millions of dollars in soft money accounts which they give to state 
and local affiliates fo dukakis courts seniors 
