<TEXT>
hurricane helenes winds strengthened to 110 mph in 
the midatlantic on thursday but forecasters said the storm was 
still no threat to land 
at 1030 pm edt the center of the 250mile wide storm was at 
latitude 141 north and longitude 443 west or about 1020 miles 
east of the caribbean island of barbados 
helene was moving westnorthwest at 10 mph and was expected to 
continue that track and speed through thursday 
this is a very good hurricane its already something to 
reckon with national hurricane center forecaster miles lawrence 
said but the currents suggest it is going to turn to the north 
its just too early to speculate 
air currents from a low pressure trough over the ocean may draw 
helene northward into the open atlantic away from the caribbean 
islands and north america lawrence said 
helene showed signs of northwest movement by late thursday but 
if it heads into the eastern caribbean islands could be affected 
by early next week said lawrence 
in the meantime helene was growing stronger and more organized 
as it moved westward across the atlantic from its spawning grounds 
near the the cape verde islands off the african coast 
helene is the eighth named storm of the 1988 atlantic hurricane 
season storms become hurricanes when sustained winds reach a 
minimum 74 mph 
of the seasons three previous hurricanes gilbert swept across 
the caribbean and mexico killing hundreds but the other two 
florence and debby caused only minor damage in mexico and the us 
gulf coast 
