<TEXT>
un secretarygeneral javier 
perez de cuellar said thursday that independence is closer than 
ever for southwest africa 
the territory commonly known as namibia is africas last 
colony and has been ruled by south africa in defiance of united 
nations resolutions 
perez de cuellar arrived early thursday on his first visit to 
south africa since 1983 to discuss recent regional peace 
initiatives which have revived the uns 10yearold plan for 
namibian independence 
we are closer than ever to a solution to the problem the 
peruvian diplomat said at a cocktail party after a day of talks 
with namibian and south african officials 
we hope that in the very near future you will have next to our 
country a sister republic the republic of namibia he said 
earlier perez de cuellar met for more than two hours with 
foreign minister pik botha both emerged to say progress had been 
made 
botha was host of the subsequent reception attended by more 
than 200 guests of all races at a former presidential residence in 
pretoria 
i would be kidding you if i said the un was a popular 
concept in south africa botha told perez de cuellar at the 
reception but it is a privilege to have you here 
south africa has agreed to end its 73year rule over namibia and 
allow un observers to oversee the transition to independence but 
only if the estimated 50000 cuban troops in neighboring angola 
withdraw 
cuba has agreed in principle to withdraw its troops but there 
is dispute over the timetable usmediated talks involving 
angola cuba and south africa aimed at setting this timetable are 
to resume monday in brazzaville congo 
most opposition parties in namibia rejected an invitation by 
perez de cuellar to come to pretoria for consultations but members 
of the territorys transitional multiracial cabinet met with him 
for more than an hour thursday 
perez de cuellar was scheduled to meet president pw botha on 
friday then travel to angola for talks with leaders of its marxist 
government 
