<TEXT>
with jobs scarce at home so many 
filipinos have gone to work abroad that they have become one of 
their countrys main sources of foreign currency and a key factor 
in keeping the economy going 
hundreds of thousands leave each year and many of them are 
trained workers who take jobs far below their capabilities because 
of the higher pay abroad 
teachers for example work as maids overseas because the wages 
are much higher than a teachers salary at home 
even so president corazon aquino calls these export workers the 
philippines new heroes 
the estimated 15 million to 25 million overseas contract 
workers remain a steady source of income for the countrys 
faltering economy 
overseas workers sent home 7919 million in 1987 making them 
the countrys third largest source of foreign exchange after 
exports of electronic components and garments central bank figures 
indicate that foreignworker remittances for the first half of 1988 
totaled 4193 million 
the money doesnt go directly to the philippines government but 
the government benefits by its flowing into the economy 
in general the workers send some of their foreign wages home to 
their families the families exchange the foreign currencies at 
banks or other financial houses for philippines pesos the foreign 
currencies then circulate through the philippines financial system 
the currencies might be purchased by a philippines importer for 
example to buy foreign goods or by the government to pay off part 
of the nations foreign debt 
tomas achacoso director of the philippine overseas employment 
administration poea says 450000 workers with contracts approved 
by his agency left for work abroad last year 
that does not include uncounted thousands who leave without 
seeking help from the poea those with poea approved contracts 
included 60000 maids some of whom left skilled professions in the 
philippines to work as domestics abroad 
achacoso said the exodus has left shortages in some key skills 
at home shipping companies for example say they have problems 
finding skippers for ferry boats in the philippines archipelago as 
well as crews for domestic oil and chemical tankers 
nurses are also in short supply and pretty soon we might 
have a shortage of computer experts or programmers achacoso said 
but achacoso denies there has been a brain drain and he 
said the foreign exchange earnings outweigh the disadvantages are 
you cant speak of a brain drain because most of these people 
do not have jobs here he said those who were employed here 
and left simply opened up positions for the unemployed here 
president aquino told filipino maids in hong kong last april 
that overseas workers helped reduce the unemployment rate to about 
9 percent and if they had remained at home you could have been 
part of that statistic 
the worker exodus began in the mid1970s when persian gulf oil 
countries hired thousands of foreigners to build roads office 
buildings hotels and homes and to manage new development projects 
even though the oil boom has faded the middle east remains the 
major destination of filipino workers saudi arabia alone employs 
at least 300000 of them as nurses office clerks public transport 
drivers janitors and as private servants 
families of overseas workers often are the only ones with money 
to build homes or buy new appliances in rural areas 
but overseas workers sometimes suffer abuses 
the problems are with those who go there as tourists he 
said the moment their visas expire they are open to a lot of 
abuses and they can range from rape to being forced into 
prostitution nonpayment of salaries and being beaten up 
ernesto catequista a 31yearold accountant recently applied 
for a job abroad with poea 
id like office work clerical bookkeeping anything he 
told the associated press he added that he had earned 2500 pesos 
125 a month at a local bank until it closed in 1985 he has 
since been earning about the same amount selling encyclopedias 
because he cannot find a steady job 
josefina pahilga 38 who trained as a teacher took a job as a 
maid abroad after she could not find a teaching post and ended up 
earning 2000 pesos 100 a month rolling cigarettes in a tobacco 
factory 
as a maid in western europe she earns the equivalent of 450 a 
month plus free board and lodging and has seen much of the world 
before coming home on for a sixmonth leave she joined her german 
employer on a family ski vacation in bulgaria 
others cite reasons beyond economics for working abroad 
its always the money and going to the united states said 
a former xray technician who works as a maid in cairo egypt 
they always think it will be easier to get to the united states 
from other countries than from the philippines 
</TEXT>
