<TEXT>
the securities industry is expected to mount a 
constitutional challenge to new massachusetts regulations designed 
to protect small investors by barring agreements that prevent 
investors from suing their stockbrokers 
responding to a flood of investor complaints after last years 
stock market crash massachusetts today becomes the first state to 
ban such agreements the new regulations outlaw contracts that 
require arbitration in disputes over losses 
securities industry officials say massachusetts is treading on 
thin constitutional ice in enacting the guidelines because the us 
supreme court last year upheld contracts that make arbitration 
agreements a precondition for doing business 
any lender has preconditions on what terms they lend you 
money william j fitzpatrick general counsel of the securities 
industry association said wednesday its not unreasonable to 
say if we have a dispute were not going to go through the very 
expensive and inefficient method of litigation 
fitzpatrick who testified against the massachusetts rule at a 
july hearing predicted securities industry groups would sue the 
state over the mandatory arbitration ban 
officials said 16 other states are planning similar regulations 
massachusetts new rules to be filed today by the secretary of 
states office take effect jan 1 1989 
were concerned about investors having a choice said deputy 
secretary of state martin t meehan we dont want them to be in 
a position where they have no choice but to sign away their day in 
court 
most brokerage firms require customers to settle disputes 
through an arbitration hearing sponsored by the new york stock 
exchange the national association of securities dealers or other 
market organizations 
arbitration is cheaper and faster than suing but investors have 
only a limited right to appeal while big institutional investors 
can negotiate contracts with brokerages individual investors 
usually have little choice but to agree often unknowingly to 
arbitration 
a securities and exchange commission survey this year of 65 
firms handling 90 percent of all customer accounts found virtually 
all require arbitration particularly for customers who borrow 
money from the firm through margin accounts or trade in risky stock 
options 
massachusetts officials said they have received hundreds of 
complaints since the oct 19 market crash from disgruntled 
investors who didnt realize they had waived their right to sue for 
losses 
the new york stock exchange said it received 1175 arbitration 
cases through august compared with 616 for the same period of 1987 
and a total of 1000 for all last year 
securities lawyers said mandatory arbitration agreements often 
are buried in boilerplate gobbledygook of contracts in sections 
on margin accounts or options 
i know of very few industries that try to incorporate such 
restrictions in their agreements or have been allowed to do that to 
such an extent said earl cantwell a buffalo ny securities 
lawyer who opposes mandatory arbitration 
cantwell said the market crash led to more investor complaints 
only because people started losing money 
one two three years before the crash a lot of improper 
practices by brokers simply went unnoticed or wouldnt be focused 
on by investigators because things were going well he said 
in addition to the state action a bill introduced in congress 
in july would make it illegal for a broker to turn away a 
customers business for refusing to sign an arbitration clause and 
would reform the arbitration process 
it would probably be more beneficial if the arbitration system 
itself was fairer and took into consideration the customers point 
of view more frequently than it does now said maria crawford 
scott editor of the journal of the chicagobased american 
association of individual investors 
analysts say the system favors brokers because investors are 
allowed a limited number of challenges and arbitration boards 
generally consist of former securities officials and can be 
insensitive to small investors concerns 
arbitration remains and probably will remain the primary 
dispute resolution for customers with complaints against their 
brokers said james c meyer president of the north american 
securities administrators association an organization of state 
regulators but that doesnt mean it should be exclusive or 
individuals should be denied their fundamental rights 
the association said the number of its arbitration cases 
quintupled from 800 in 1980 to 4100 last year and could climb 
above 6000 this year 
but fitzpatrick said only a very small percentage of complaints 
to the sec are about arbitration he said most brokerage firms 
dont require customers with cash accounts to sign arbitration 
clauses and customers who want to borrow money on margin can go to 
banks or elsewhere 
according to the secretary of states office the 16 other 
states planning to impose similar regulations are alaska 
colorado florida georgia idaho indiana iowa north dakota 
ohio oregon pennsylvania south dakota tennessee virginia 
washington and wisconsin 
