similar advertising plan in their state 
gms chevrolet motors division planned to increase the amount 
its dealer franchises pay for their cars by 1 percent an average 
of 40 to 50 a car to finance a dealers association that would 
run the automakers national advertising campaigns 
the company offered dealers who joined the association a 25 
percent discount on the surcharge but told those who did not join 
that they would not receive the discount brown said wednesday in 
announcing the settlement 
under the plan the dealers would pass on the surcharge to car 
buyers chevrolet planned to begin the program with its september 
shipments and tacked the 1 percent charge on to its dealers bills 
for this month 
a lot of dealers complained about it brown said 
brown said he learned about the chevrolet plan in august steve 
herndon solicitor general for the attorney generals office 
investigated the plan then informed chevrolet that it violated 
west virginia law 
under the law autmobile dealers cannot be required to 
participate in a dealers association 
this type of deceptive business practice is a violation of 
fair trade competition and the consumer is the ultimate victim 
brown said 
obviously if gm dealers have to compete with other gm dealers 
in advertising it means better prices for consumers herndon 
said 
the attorney generals office and chevrolet last week negotiated 
a settlement under which dealers will participate in the ad plan 
only if they want and then pay the discounted fee those who dont 
participate will be paid an amount equivalent to the 25 percent 
discount 
dealers did not pay the september charge herndon said 
at least 27 other states have auto dealer laws similar to west 
virginias the attorney general said 
