<DOCNO> AP880922-0220 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
today marks the third anniversary of the plaza 
accord a fivenation agreement that might be described as the 
kelloggbriand pact of the financial world 
the kelloggbriand pact of 1928 was an international agreement 
to renounce war as an instrument of national policy in light of 
subsequent conflicts world war ii comes immediately to mind 
kelloggbriand was a miserable failure 
the plaza accord of sept 22 1985 was an agreement by the 
united states britain west germany france and japan to push down 
the exchange value of the dollar the idea was that a cheaper 
dollar would help shrink the us trade deficit and reduce 
protectionist sentiments in congress 
at first the plaza accord looked like a smash success the 
dollar tumbled all through 1985 and 1986 and into 1987 only a few 
impolite skeptics said the dollar would have fallen even without 
the accord 
then some funny things happened first the finance ministers 
got together again at the louvre in paris in february 1987 and 
decided that further declines in the dollar would be 
counterproductive 
naturally the dollar kept falling then it rose then it fell 
steeply at the end of 1987 this year it has risen up a fat 14 
percent against a marketbasket of foreign currencies since jan 1 
in light of these gyrations it has begun to seem as though the 
finance leaders are standing at the bow of an ocean liner with a 
toy wheel trying to convince the other passengers they are 
steering 
all this time people began to notice the cheaper dollar was not 
working wonders on the trade deficit instead of shrinking the gap 
set records in 1986 and again in 1987 it has taken until this year 
to see big improvements 
as time went on it has become increasingly clear that 
1 central bankers and finance ministers dont have much control 
over currency rates 
2 currency rates do not have nearly as much to do with trade 
balances as everyone had thought 
this is not to say the 3yearold plaza accord was a waste of 
time it was a valuable beginning toward cooperation in an 
interdependent world but this is where the comparison with 
kelloggbriand comes in 
in 1985 as in 1928 agreements between nations depend on the 
signatories willingness to adapt their national goals to the 
greater international good and that is a hard sell 
currency rates will never be stable as long as nations pursue 
widely differing economic policies abhorrence of inflation in west 
germany vs relative tolerance of it in the united states for 
example 
the gold standard for currencies forced policy coordination on 
the nations but its fatal flaw was that it put all the burden of 
adjustment on weakcurrency countries that gave undue leverage to 
the slowgrowth west germanys of the world 
businesses want stable currency rates so they can plan where to 
locate plants how much to manufacture for export from which 
nations to buy components and so on 
three years after the plaza accord however the goal of stable 
currencies is beginning to look like a distant dream economists 
estimates of the proper value of the dollar are all over the 
map from 100 yen to 200 yen the current rate is 134 
differing economic policies have something to do with the 
instability as do differing predictions for the trade deficit 
adding to the complexity is that trade flows are not the only 
controlling factor in rates investment flows are at least as 
important meaning that if japanese for whatever reason crave us 
treasury bonds and factories they will keep the dollar in strong 
demand even though they have little interest in importing american 
products 
stabilize currencies abolish war good luck 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0221 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bank of new york cos 12 billion bid for 
rival irving bank corp has staggered to the oneyear mark with 
neither side ready to throw in the towel or even call the outcome 
at first it had the distinction of being the firstever hostile 
takeover fight between two big american banks now it has become 
the lengthiest such battle among major us corporations 
the strain of the bidding marathon clearly has taken its toll at 
both large new york institutions by distracting management from 
their usual work confusing stockholders and piling up millions of 
dollars in legal and other expenses 
a third friendly contender milanbased banca commerciale 
italiana spa recently was forced out of the running due to an 
unfavorable ruling by the federal reserve board which is patiently 
overseeing the proposed merger process 
its the economic equivalent of the iraniraq war because of 
the length and the substantial casualties said h rodgin cohen 
an attorney for the bank of new york 
at least were not using poison gas the banks chairman j 
carter bacot said jokingly in a recent interview only poison 
pills are involved 
the outcome of the irvingbank of new york war which began on 
sept 25 1987 is likely to be decided in a new york state court 
where among other things irvings poison pill antitakeover 
defense is under attack some observers say the entire process 
could drag on into the winter 
in the meantime the takeover attempt appears to have turned 
into a struggle of personalities between bacot and irvings equally 
strongminded chairman joseph a rice 
analysts say bacot is determined to merge the two banks not only 
because the two would fit nicely together but because he fears bank 
of new york itself could become a takeover target if a big west 
coast or foreign bank decided to enter the new york market 
a merger would nearly double bank of new yorks size making it 
the 11th largest banking company in the country and a more elusive 
target 
rice analysts say has his own vision of running his bank and 
believes it is worth much more than the bank of new yorks offer 
especially given its past investments in technological advances 
both men have held only a handful of facetoface meetings since 
bacot formally proposed the merger and each time talks have broken 
off without any signs of progress no new talks are planned 
because rice said we see absolutely nothing to be gained at 
this stage 
i think the financial issues were certainly important to 
irving early on and now but it clearly has become a personal 
issue said michael starr a banking analyst for duff amp phelps 
inc in chicago 
cohen a partner of sullivan amp cromwell which has represented 
many firms in takeovers agreed my own judgment is that they 
have created this fiction that the bank of new york is evil and 
horrible its almost a crusade 
that is an unfortunate turn of events many analysts contend 
since both banks have similar markets and services and would work 
well together 
irving has waged a tough defense to bank of new yorks 
persistent overtures from poison pills to proxy fights a recently 
instituted flipin provision to its poison pill would make an 
unsolicited merger prohibitively expensive by giving all irving 
shareholders except bank of new york the right to buy 400 of 
stock for 200 once bank of new york acquires 20 percent of irving 
the irving board has taken enough action of a defensive nature 
and the burden is now on them to be able to show that they are not 
merely trying to entrench themselves and irvings management 
said abraham nad publisher of the monthly newsletter directorship 
an authority on corporate boards thats a very fine line to 
walk 
bacot says he first broached the idea of a merger at a luncheon 
with rice about five years ago rice wasnt very receptive then he 
recalled he conceded that irving probably resents the fact we 
put an offer on the table like that after it had turned down the 
bank of new york privately 
whats particularly noteworthy about this battle is that its 
occurring in an industry where hostile takeovers are rare even in 
the best of circumstances the complex timeconsuming regulatory 
requirements that other industries are spared could make some banks 
think twice about a merger 
when the bid first emerged some experts predicted hostile bids 
could become more commonplace particularly among aggressive 
regional institutions theyre not so sure anymore 
hostile takeovers have no place in banking rice said 
recently they are a severe threat to the stability of the 
banking industry and the soundness of the economy 
new ground though was broken on the regulatory front for one 
thing the fed declined to make any distinction between a friendly 
or hostile offer in approving bank of new yorks application in 
february 
and in august the fed decided to treat foreign owners of us 
banks much the same as domestic owners by requiring instituto per 
la ricostruzione industriale the parent of white knight banca 
commerciale to apply separately to the fed iri which balked at 
the idea is controlled by the italian government and accounts for 
about a quarter of italys gross national product 
irving attorney robert falise who says he was forced to devote 
all his time to the takeover fight said irving is negotiating with 
several foreign and domestic banks about a possible merger 
however analysts say if an offer happens to emerge it must be 
extremely attractive to win over shareholders at this late date 
banca commerciale had offered 84 a share for 51 percent of 
irvings approximately 18 million common shares outstanding before 
withdrawing its bid the merger proposal was part of a complex 
defensive restructuring plan that included sale of irving assets 
costcutting measures and a special cash dividend 
bank of new york which owns about 49 percent of irving is 
offering 15 in cash and 1575 shares of its own stock for each of 
irvings roughly 18 million common shares outstanding 
bacot maintains his bid is just as attracive now as it was a 
year ago although the cash portion has declined significantly if 
he had to do things over again hed still bid for irving bacot 
said 
we wouldnt have stuck with it that long unless we felt that 
way he said it gets a little frustrating you have to have a 
lot of patience 
