<TEXT>
several senators today criticized airline 
deregulation and the rash of mergers it has spawned complaining 
they have given large air carriers monopoly power in some parts of 
the country and resulted in higher fares but less service 
simply stated people are paying more to fly today because the 
airlines have developed monopoly hubs declared sen ernest 
hollings dsc chairman of the senate commerce committee 
he complained that a fare from washington to charleston sc 
was 120 in 1977 before airline deregulation but that recently he 
paid 510 for the same trip 
but the committee at a hearing aimed at examining airline 
pricing practices were told by transportation secretary jim burnley 
that air travelers have benefited by the deregulation of the 
industry with average air fares declining 13 percent in the last 
decade 
he attributed an average 8 percent increase in domestic air 
fares during the first six months of the year to increased costs 
for fuel new aircraft and a number of governmentrequired safety 
initiatives 
as an example of competition benefiting air travelers burnley 
cited a recent decision by continental airlines to offer a 39 
offseason fare between the northeast and florida 
airline deregulation has resulted in a substantial improvement 
in overall competition to the benefit of the public insisted 
burnley 
but the explanation didnt satisfy a number of the senators 
including hollings sen john danforth rmo and sen larry 
pressler rsd who said fares and service to their parts of the 
country have suffered 
its cheaper to fly across the nation than it is to fly across 
south dakota that is a very bizarre situation complained 
pressler who suggested some reregulation would be in order 
that would require ticket prices to be linked to miles traveled 
hollings and danforth the ranking repubican on the committee 
also warned that airline fare and service practices could lead to 
some additional government controls on the industry 
in certain airports competition does not exist airlines get a 
lock on an airport and when they get a lock they can do pretty much 
what they please declared danforth 
he cited trans world airlines dominance at st louis where the 
airline controls 83 percent of the flights since its merger two 
years ago with ozark air line once its chief competitor single 
airlines also dominate at minneapolis pittsburgh and memphis said 
danforth 
burnley however defended his departments approval of 21 
airline mergers in recent years and maintained that even at the 
airports cited by the senators competition has been maintained 
not only has new entry by airlines occurred at each of these 
hubs but competing incumbent carriers continue to provide 
competitive service said burnley 
but when pressed by danforth burnely said the department has 
been disappointed at the level of competition as st louis lambert 
field since twas merger with ozark 
he said the department had expected for example that southwest 
airlines would move into the competitive void created by the 
twaozark merger with as many as 60 flights a day instead of the 22 
or 23 flights a day it currently operates through st louis 
id like to know why that has occurred said burnley 
promising the department would examine the competitive situation at 
the airport 
